    "abstract": [],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Coronavirus disease 2019 (Covid-19) is a highly contagious disease that has the potential to spread rapidly among healthcare workers (HCWs) and in the hospital setting [1] . A critical epidemiological measure that modulates the early stage of a viral outbreak is the access to adequate equipment, that is crucial for HCWs' protection [2] . However, the present pandemic is distinguished by a huge shortage of personal protective equipment [3] , especially in Italy where HCWs seem to experience high rates of severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) infection. The Italian Government strengthened prevention and restraint strategies, including self-quarantine, and restricted resident movements first in Lombardy and subsequently across the entire country [4] . Besides, while in the early phase of the pandemic routine screening for SARS-CoV-2 infection has been easily provided for politicians and football players, even in absence of overt symptoms, by the end of March no specific serial testing strategy had been implemented for early recognition of potentially infected HCWs [5] . It was expected that initial reports from China during the early epidemic phase might have worldwide increased the awareness among healthcare providers of the high infectious risks in a hospital environment. Unfortunately, in the region of Lombardy, the epicentre of the Italian outbreak, at least 42 physicians died for Covid-19 as April 1, 2020 [6] and international media and Italian politicians are now raising the question: are we doing enough to protect HCWs during this pandemic?",
