            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Sir,"
        },
        {
            "text": "Currently, there are no published studies specifically focused on the prevalence of Covid-19 infection among HCWs.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Sir,"
        },
        {
            "text": "Hence, we investigated the proportion of HCWs among consecutive Covid-19 patients admitted in a tertiary care hospital, located in Lombardy, at the epicentre of the Italian pandemic, during the early stage of the European outbreak. . We evaluated the rate of infected HCWs on the overall population and on active-workers, excluding retired patients. Sixty-five patients were HCWs, representing the 16.3% of our total population. All cases were Lombardy-related HCWs exposures. According to the latest report of \"Italian Statistical Institute\", the overall proportion of HCWs is estimated to be 1.87% of the adult population, therefore the proportion of HCWs in our series is about 9 times more than expected. Our sample included 120 retired patients; if we consider only active-workers, 65 out of 280 cases were HCWs (23.2%). As HCWs behaviors and control measures were continually in flux, we estimated the proportion of HCWs infected over time until the end of March, 40 days after the first registered Italian patient. Figure 1 shows that the transmission rate in HCWs has persistently increased affecting up to 29% of admitted active-workers in the upper quartile of the HCWs volume distribution.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 1022,
                    "end": 1030,
                    "text": "Figure 1",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "section": "Sir,"
        },
        {
            "text": "Until 30 March, 2020, general data provided from the Italian \"Istituto Superiore di Sanit\u00e0\" showed that among 94.312 confirmed Covid-19 cases 8.956 were HCW (9.49%, vs 16.3% of our population). Moreover, up to 24 February, 2020, China reported that 2.055 out of 77.262 Covid-19 cases were HCW (2.66%) [7] : despite the increased awareness of infection risks, the prevalence of SARS-CoV-2 infections seems to be three-times higher in Italian HCWs than in Chinese HCWs, that were the first to face Covid-19 outbreak.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 301,
                    "end": 304,
                    "text": "[7]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF6"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Sir,"
        },
        {
            "text": "The present analysis indicates that current Italian outbreak of Covid-19 is having a considerable impact on local HCWs.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Sir,"
        },
        {
            "text": "Despite government efforts to limit the spread of SARS-CoV-2 infections, the lack of standardized protocols to screen HCWs all over the country, even during this later phase of the pandemic, may induce the resumption of new outbreaks in the hospital environment, especially as soon as routine activities will be restored. Although this study is limited to a single nation, our data highlight the urgent need of implementing serial testing and appropriate control measures among HCWs and may also provide some valuable guidance for other countries facing Covid-19 outbreak.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Sir,"
        }
    ],
